LoSBoL

2009-11-02 06:37:00 UTC
As far as I know there is only one sping kit for all the SD versions, standard and R... What makes the difference is the setup made by the specialist who installed the system.
The sping are the ones with the Hyperprogressive patented technolgy by Hyperpro and are full progressive, along the whole stroke.

Now the bike is softer on the road, you can feel more confidence when braking and leaning and when hitting bumps or holes wether you are on a straight or bent line... IMHO a huge improvement, far from the standard setup. The fork oil il SAE10 and the level is @ 140mm . Is also a good setup for track use if not seeking to squeeze the ultimate time lap. In that case compression and rebound shuld be tightened, while the preload not.
A side effect is that you can use the tyres with a higher pression also on the track, so that they are firmer, they last longer and better!

My better spent money as for the Motobox and the Akrapovic!!

2010-03-21 18:18:00 UTC
So first day of spring and I finally get a 300+ mile ride. Package going really well with all the winter mods finished. Main ones are Motobox, PC111, SAS junked and shortened Akras converted to carbon sleeves.

Getting custom map on Tuesday so I will be very interested in seeing the first run because bike appears to be flawless fueling as is (on Akra map and whatever the PC111 came with a s base setting).

After getting used to the bike again on full throttle I think I need a shorter action throttle. And a steering damper - had a few 120mph shakes on bumpy A roads and the bike is definitely giving more torque as it goes front end light a lot more in second gear hard acceleration. I have resisted one up to now and followed the endless debates about them here but if you ride fast on UK roads I think you need one.

Or maybe it was just my enthusiasm.

The R-seat is not uncomfortable, it's just hard. There's a distinct difference. It's very wide, so it doesn't feel like you're flossing your butt-hole. There's no problems with moving around on it. The only real complaint I have about it is that it's quite slippery. Solutions to that is sticky leathers and/or to put some sticky residue on the seat. Or stomp-grips.

And keep in mind, it's "", not "Custom", not "GT", not "Gold Wing".... R..!! R!! It's not supposed to be "comfortable".
So if you're an "All show - No Go" there's your punishment already.

2011-01-17 08:03:00 UTC
I finally got a good group ride in on the Superduke today. The weather was most excellent here in Santa Cruz Cali! On my bike was the newly installed Motohooligan box with the secondary flies, sas removal, and crash bungs. I also tested the CRG Arrow mirror. I was quite impressed with the mirror, lots of visibility and stable. It's true what they tell you about the motohooligan box! It certainly does smooth out the throttle. Bike felt way different going into and exiting corners and is much more tolerable at slow pace city riding. The Motohooligan Box is by far the best mod I have done to my bike. I'm still running the stock cans and havent remapped yet, but there is definitely a noticeable improvement.

KTM666

2011-08-25 00:22:00 UTC
So just got back from about 70 miles round trip rippin it ..... Cord showing last 4 rides - yup mistake i know ... Was at 120mph uphill today on this rear tyre - the cord lengthened itself by about 8 inches - was only half that size before this latest romp...

I tried to do as KTM GUY suggests and wear the sides out before the middle , but i just have a hard time staying off the throttle on this bike. slightly over 2 months ago i bought this tyre and said "i'm going to go easy on the straights" so i can wear the sides first ---- Well that sure didn't happen.... i think i got about 3,000 miles out of it though ... I like the tyre - Dunlop Q2's the new ones. And the deal on them lately 200 bucks for a set is hard to pass up , and i've never had the tyres give while hard cornering ,

Really getting used to reverse shifting , My unasked for advice to anyone going to put the reverse shift kit on is -DO NOT try racing around through twisties etc until you're sure yu have all the reflexes , and mistake proof nerve patterns before you start ripping ... I ride quite a bit of serious twisties and today was my 7th outing on reverse shifting .. I"m just about up to speed.

have fun



i forgot to mention - i encourage any of you eager eaters ( like i am ) to loose the weight - i have lost about 10 lbs from 200 to 190 on my 5'8" whole inches of body and i tell you the bike's acceleration is getting quicker , i'm gona shoot for another 10 lbs and get down to 180 lbs....

Bike really seems to be enjoying it (-:

That's coz the front pressure is right and the rear is too low mate.

They're not the same as motorsport handmade N Techs.

Hot pressures of Sportsmarts on an SD 32 front 30 rear. Will grip ok and won't tear up.

Just of top of my head without checking my notes I'm sure cold pressures are usually 4psi lower.


Bit of topic like

Just for comparison...
Those Interacts I sent, the rear had very slight cold tear. It only took 2psi more pressure to get it running clean.

There's how the new ones look running just 2psi more. Don't even look like they've been on track.

In Italy if the value of the bike is less than the damage the insurance pays you the Eurotax value, so you can buy yourself a similar used bike, like the old beloved you couldn't repair. Then you have to destroy the bike in an authorised center (i.e: you give to the center the frame, the plate and the certificate of ownership and so the bike officially isn't existent any more). Then again with all the stuff you've streaked from your ex-bike you fund the purchase of a used bike like yours or a new one. So I have to choose between a 2008 SD, a SD-R 132 or (hopefully) an Aprila Tuono V4... who knows... The only problem is the big loss of time... two months have been passed and i wonder how many other will, before I'll get my money from the French insurance...

Hope to have a bike for the two days KTM Test'N'Track in Mugello Circuit at the end of March...
